,{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 49-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of left sided abdominal pain. The pain started gradually and is now constant in nature. She reports constipation for the past 2 days. Her last menstrual period was two weeks earlier. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 126/82 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is marked tenderness with guarding in the left iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diverticulitis","Ureteric colic","Ischaemic colitis","Mid-cycle bleed","Epiploic appendagitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classical features of acute \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic features include left lower quadrant pain, fever, constipation, and localised tenderness in the left iliac fossa. Diverticulitis occurs when diverticula (small pouches that form in the wall of the colon) become inflamed or infected. The sigmoid colon is the most common site for diverticula formation in Western populations, explaining the left-sided predominance of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe distribution of the pain might fit for \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric colic\u003C/strong\u003E, but the area of tenderness would be unusual. Ureteric colic typically presents with severe, colicky flank pain that may radiate to the groin.  Localised tenderness can be associated with ureteric stone disease and would be suggestive of obstruction - but in such instances the tenderness would be expected to be over the kidney itself. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA possible diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemic colitis \u003C/strong\u003Eshould always be kept in mind - but this tends to occur in older patients and those with a history of cardiovascular disease. The pain is often associated with bloody diarrhea rather than constipation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotential gynaecological problems must always be considered, particularly with cases of lower abdominal pain. The distribution of the area of tenderness and the presence of fever would make a \u003Cstrong\u003Emid-cycle bleed \u003C/strong\u003E(mittelschmerz) unlikely. These patients present occasionally with severe abdominal pain - often mimicking appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiploic appendagitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an uncommon, but well recognised cause of acute abdominal pain. The condition is usually self-limiting, but the symptoms can be so severe to warrant surgical intervention. This condition is usually identified and diagnosed on the CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of left lower quadrant pain, fever, constipation and localised tenderness in the left iliac fossa strongly points to acute diverticulitis as the most likely diagnosis. Definitive diagnosis would typically involve CT imaging, which would show colonic wall thickening, pericolic fat stranding, and possibly complications such as abscess formation or perforation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diverticulitis typically presents with left lower quadrant pain, fever, and altered bowel habits in middle-aged or older adults.","Localised tenderness in the left iliac fossa with fever is highly suggestive of diverticulitis in the absence of other significant medical history."],"references":["Young-Fadok TM. Diverticulitis. N Engl J Med 2018; 379:1635-42. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30354951/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97089"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97089"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T09:36:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T09:38:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"